-32.%09 The mandate of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission is listed under Schedule N of the Indian Residential Schools Settlement Agreement, http://www.residentialschoolsettlement.ca/ settlement.html (accessed 5 March 2015).%0AIn accordance with the TRC%E2%80%99s mandate, the Commission was required to recognize %E2%80%9Cthe significance of Aboriginal oral and legal traditions in its activities,%E2%80%9D Schedule N, 4(d); and %E2%80%9Cwitness, support, promote and facilitate truth and reconciliation events at both the national and community levels,%E2%80%9D Schedule N, 1(c).%0AThe term witness %E2%80%9Crefers to the Aboriginal principle of %E2%80%98witnessing,%E2%80%99%E2%80%9D Indian Residential Schools Settlement Agreement, Schedule N, 1(c), n1.%0AAboriginal oral history, legal traditions, and the principle of witnessing have deep historical roots and contemporary relevance for reconciliation.%0AIndigenous law was used to resolve family and community conflict, to establish Treaties among various Indigenous nations, and to negotiate nation-to-nation treaties with the Crown.%0AFor a comprehensive history of Aboriginal%E2%80%93Crown Treaty making from contact to the present, see: Miller, Compact, Contract, Covenant.%0AThe term witness is in reference to the Aboriginal principle of witnessing, which varies among First Nations, M%C3%A9tis, and Inuit peoples.%0AGenerally speaking, witnesses are called to be the keepers of history when an event of historic significance occurs.%0AThrough witnessing, the event or work that is undertaken is validated and provided legitimacy.%0AThe work could not take place without honoured and respected guests to witness it.%0AWitnesses are asked to store and care for the history they witness and to share it with their own people when they return home.%0AFor Aboriginal peoples, the act of witnessing these events comes with a great responsibility to remember all the details and be able to recount them accurately as the foundation of ora